{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d0fa769a-7503-4334-abd9-222326d47fd8","content":"The migration is straightforward. In your project file, simply **remove** (or set to `false`) the `<UseVSTest>` property:\n\n```xml\n<Project Sdk=\"MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0\">\n  <PropertyGroup>\n-   <UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>\n  </PropertyGroup>\n</Project>\n```\n\nThat's it. Starting with MSTest.Sdk 3.4+, **Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default** runner. Setting `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` was opting you back into the legacy VSTest infrastructure.\n\n**Key differences to be aware of:**\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| CLI | Use `dotnet test` as before, but you can also run the test exe directly |\n| Test filtering | `--filter` still works; platform also supports `--filter-expression` |\n| Extensions | VSTest adapters → Microsoft.Testing.Platform extensions (MSTest ones are auto-included by the SDK) |\n| CI output | TRX logger still available via `--results-directory` / `--logger trx` |\n\nIf you have a `.runsettings` file, it's still supported. If you relied on custom VSTest adapters or data collectors, verify they have Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d0981710-89eb-4783-aeeb-9e90dc5d430f","outputTokens":311,"requestId":"6811:163A9A:785205:7F7F7E:6A044D54"},"id":"11766cba-4748-471d-b0ff-e9ad26c63814","timestamp":"2026-05-13T10:07:32.151Z","parentId":"37648341-faf0-4e0f-a771-e214c0072e50"}
